#Text=Robert Hungerford , 3rd Baron Hungerford
#Text=Robert Hungerford , 3rd Baron Hungerford ( c.1429 – 1464 ) was an English nobleman .
#Text=He supported the Lancastrian cause in the War of the Roses .
#Text=In the late 1440s and early 1450s he was a member of successive parliaments .
#Text=He was a prisoner of the French for much of the 1450s until his mother arranged a payment of a 7,966 l ransom .
#Text=In 1460 after successive defeats on the battlefield he fled with Henry VI to Scotland .
#Text=In 1461 he was attainted in Edward IV 's first parliament , and executed in Newcastle soon after he was captured at the Battle of Hexham .
#Text=Early life
#Text=Hungerford was son and heir of Robert Hungerford , 2nd Baron Hungerford , and was grandson of Walter Hungerford , 1st Baron Hungerford ( died 1449 ) . [ 4 ]
#Text=Hungerford was summoned to parliament as Baron Moleyns in 1445 , and received a like summons until 1453 . [ 4 ]
#Text=Dispute with John Paston
#Text=In 1448
#Text=Hungerford began a fierce quarrel with John Paston regarding the ownership of the manor of Gresham in Norfolk .
#Text=Hungerford , acting on the advice of John Heydon , a solicitor of Baconsthorpe , took forcible possession of the estate on 17 February 1448 .
#Text=William Waynflete , bishop of Winchester , made a vain attempt at arbitration .
#Text=Paston obtained repossession , but on 28 January 1450 Hungerford sent a thousand men to dislodge him .
#Text=After threatening to kill Paston , who was absent , Hungerford 's adherents violently assaulted Paston 's wife Margaret , but Hungerford finally had to surrender the manor to Paston . [ 5 ]
#Text=French wars
#Text=In 1452
#Text=Hungerford accompanied John Talbot , 2nd Earl of Shrewsbury , to Aquitaine , and was taken prisoner while endeavouring to raise the siege of Chastillon .
#Text=His ransom was fixed at 7,966 l . , and his mother sold her plate and mortgaged her estates to raise the money .
#Text=His release was effected in 1459 , after seven years and four months ' imprisonment .

#Text=In consideration of his misfortunes he was granted , in the year of his return to England , licence to export fifteen hundred sacks of wool to foreign ports without paying duty , and received permission to travel abroad .
#Text=He thereupon visited Florence . [ 4 ]
#Text=Wars of the Roses
#Text=In 1460
#Text=Hungerford was home again , and took a leading part on the Lancastrian side in the Wars of the Roses .

#Text=In June 1460 he retired with Lord Scales and other of his friends to the Tower of London , on the entry of the Earl of Warwick and his Kentish followers into the city ; but after the defeat of the Lancastrians at the battle of Northampton ( 10 July 1460 ) , Hungerford and his friends surrendered the Tower to the Yorkists on the condition that he and Lord Scales should depart free , [ 6 ]
#Text=After taking part in the Battle of Towton ( 29 March 1461 ) — a further defeat for the Lancastrians — Hungerford fled with Henry VI to York , and thence into Scotland .
#Text=He visited France in the summer to obtain help for Henry and Margaret , and was arrested by the French authorities in August 1461 .
#Text=Writing to Margaret at the time from Dieppe , he begged her not to lose heart . [ 7 ]
#Text=He was attainted in Edward IV 's first parliament in November 1461 .

#Text=He afterward met with some success in his efforts to rally the Lancastrians in the north of England , but was taken prisoner at the Battle of Hexham on 15 May 1464 , and was executed at Newcastle .
#Text=He was buried in Salisbury Cathedral .
#Text=On 5 August 1460 many of his lands were granted to Richard , Duke of Gloucester ( afterward Richard III ) .
#Text=Other portions of his property were given to Lord Wenlock , who was directed by Edward IV to make provision for Hungerford 's wife and young children . [ 8 ]
#Text=Marriage and children
#Text=Hungerford married at a very early age ( about 1441 )
#Text=Eleanor ( born 1426 ) , daughter and heiress of Sir William Moleyns ( died 1429 ) . [ 4 ]
#Text=Among their children were : [ 8 ]
#Text=Sir Thomas Hungerford of Rowden
#Text=Sir Walter Hungerford of Farleigh
#Text=Eleanor survived her husband and subsequently married Sir Oliver Manningham .
#Text=She was buried at Stoke Poges , Buckinghamshire , in 1476 . [ 8 ]
